            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 8,
            "is_accepted": true,
            "last_activity_date": 1351049725,
            "creation_date": 1351049090,
            "body": "<p>Depending on where you want to trap the \"enter\" key, you could use an <code>ActionListener<\/code> (on such components such as text components or buttons) or attach a <a href=\"http://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/uiswing/misc/keybinding.html\" rel=\"noreferrer\">key binding<\/a> to you component<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>public class MyPanel extends JPanel {\n\n    public MyPanel() {\n\n        InputMap im = getInputMap(WHEN_FOCUSED);\n        ActionMap am = getActionMap();\n\n        im.put(KeyStroke.getKeyStroke(KeyEvent.VK_ENTER, 0), \"onEnter\");\n\n        am.put(\"onEnter\", new AbstractAction() {\n            @Override\n            public void actionPerformed(ActionEvent e) {\n                // Enter pressed\n            }\n        });\n\n    }\n\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>This will rely on the component being focused.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 13042560,
            "question_id": 13042504,
            "last_edit_date": 1351049725
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/fF4h5.jpg?s=256",
                "account_id": 1165812,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 1144176,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1144176/jake-stoeffler",
                "reputation": 2915,
                "display_name": "Jake Stoeffler"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 6,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1351050411,
            "creation_date": 1351049723,
            "body": "<p>One way is to implement the <a href=\"http://docs.oracle.com/javase/1.5.0/docs/api/java/awt/event/KeyListener.html\" rel=\"noreferrer\"><code>KeyListener<\/code><\/a> interface and its key event methods.  For example,<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>public class MyClass  implements KeyListener {\n    public void keyTyped(KeyEvent e) {\n        // Invoked when a key has been typed.\n    }\n\n    public void keyPressed(KeyEvent e) {\n        // Invoked when a key has been pressed.\n        if (e.getKeyCode() == KeyEvent.VK_ENTER &amp;&amp; yourOtherCondition) {\n            myMethod();\n        }\n    }\n\n    public void keyReleased(KeyEvent e) {\n        // Invoked when a key has been released.\n    }\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Then add this listener with<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>myComponent.addKeyListener(new MyClass());\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Or if you prefer,<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>myComponent.addKeyListener(new KeyListener() {\n    public void keyPressed(KeyEvent e) { /* ... */ }\n\n    public void keyReleased(KeyEvent e) { /* ... */ }\n\n    public void keyTyped(KeyEvent e) { /* ... */ }\n});\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/uiswing/events/keylistener.html\" rel=\"noreferrer\">See this<\/a> for more details.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 13042644,
            "question_id": 13042504,
            "last_edit_date": 1351050411
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/c6087948c4623b8f9633796e254bcf0b?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
